Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-fearing dinosaurs: the two-foot-long and 1.50-foot-long animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongate skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle collars and a long tail.
Had the species lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
However, Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the Pangäa Supercontinent.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the relationship relationships, the spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs on one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
Over the course of the excavation, they carried together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino history
