Support for brake maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As in the case of the ABS anti-blocking brake system at the time, and as is now done with the SEP stability control, the aid systems for braking in emergency situations must become a mandatory means in the European cars.
In fact, they are already required in all newly authorised passenger cars and light small transporters, for the remaining vehicles a car time was set up by the end of February 2011.
However, the European Union's decision to take care of the safety of pedestrians can also help to prevent many road traffic accidents because of their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake maneuver, which detects the system on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake force executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers engaged in an accident were no longer willing to step onto the brake pedal before the collapse, and half of them had not been stopped with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, engages in the brake system with maximum force and thereby reduces the brake time and thus also the brake distance which a car deposits during the brake process.
According to a EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents each year that harm fuss passengers could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - one calculated that any fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency brake systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that recognizes (through radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts to this, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collapse is already inevitable, the brake assistant will exert maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible in this way.
