No single accident is the same and the calculation of the costs for the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a question of minutes.
That is why almost 100% of the auditors use these types of systems.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repair collect the information they receive from the manufacturers to process them afterwards and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are made with their products.
The two other companies competing with the tool market for review and processing of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that the manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audex's sales manager, 63 manufacturers and importers work together, each of which provides the information in a different format.
The amount of data to be processed will become bigger and larger until the point that over the last five years even more versions, variants and motorizations have come to market than over the entire fifteen years.
As soon as a new car comes to the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a difficult task, because every single one of the but thousand vehicle parts must be catagolyzed and its price entered.
In addition, a “intelligent” background image is created by each model on which to “click” different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, work can be completed in a week if the procedure progresses quickly.
When it comes to a less common car, it may take up to three or four months for Audex to have full information at 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle park driving on the street, it is more than 99%.
For the purpose of performing documentation work and producing databases worldwide, Audex has eight (Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) distributed centers and each of them has specialized in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually experts for mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audex invests €90 million annually in the development of these databases.
Each month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every second day.
